  "text": "Measurement of Renal Microvascular Oxygenation and Renal Venous PO 2. The renal microvascular PO 2 (PO 2 ) within the kidney cortex and outer medulla was measured by oxygen-dependent quenching of phosphorescence using a dual-wavelength-phosphorimeter [CITATION_1] . The renal venous PO 2 ( rv PO 2 ) was detected by the same method [CITATION_2] . Briefly described, Oxyphor G2 (Oxygen Enterprises, Philadelphia, PA), intravenously infused, binds to albumin [CITATION_3] . If excited by a flash of light (wavelength ϳ440 or 630 nm), the Oxyphor G2-albumin complex emits phosphorescence (wavelength ϳ800 nm). Dependent on the oxygen concentration, the phosphorescence intensity decreases and the relationship between the measured decay-time and the PO 2 can be estimated using the Stern-Volmer relation (18 -20) . Heterogeneity in oxygen pressure was analyzed by fitting a sum of small rectangular distributions to the distributions of quencher concentration in the phosphorescence data (21).",
